        <ConversionResults gradeData={null} isGym={true} />
      </div>

      <!-- CTA after conversion -->
      <div id="cta-after-conversion" class="hidden mt-10 p-8 bg-sage/5 border border-sage/20 rounded-2xl text-center">
        <p class="text-xl font-bold text-granite mb-2">
          Ready to put these grades into practice?
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-600 mb-6">Find the best bouldering gyms near you.</p>
        <a
          href="/search"
          class="inline-flex items-center justify-center px-8 py-4 bg-sage text-white font-bold rounded-xl hover:bg-sage/90 transition-all shadow-lg hover:shadow-sage/30 transform hover:-translate-y-0.5"
        >
          Find Bouldering Gyms Near You →
        </a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Educational Content -->
  <section class="content-section py-16">
    <div class="container mx-auto px-4 max-w-4xl">
      <div class="prose prose-lg prose-headings:text-granite prose-p:text-gray-600 prose-a:text-sage hover:prose-a:text-sage/80 max-w-none">
        
        <!-- How to Use -->
        <div class="mb-16">
          <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-granite mb-6">How to Use This Converter</h2>
          <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
            Converting bouldering grades has never been easier. Simply type any grade into the search bar above - whether it's a V-Scale grade like "V5", a Fontainebleau grade like "6B", or a UK Tech grade like "6a". Our intelligent search will find the grade instantly and show you all equivalent grades across all three major systems.
          </p>
          <div class="bg-gradient-to-r from-sage/5 to-transparent border-l-4 border-sage p-6 rounded-r-xl my-8">
            <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-granite mb-2 !mt-0">The Gym vs Outdoor Toggle</h3>
            <p class="text-gray-700 !mb-0">
               This is where our tool stands out. Indoor climbing gyms typically set grades 1-2 levels softer than outdoor climbing at beginner to intermediate levels (VB-V6). Toggle between "Indoor Gym" and "Outdoor" to see adjusted grades. For example, climbing V4 at your gym might be closer to outdoor V2 or V3 - and that's completely normal!
            </p>
          </div>
          
          <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 my-10">
             <div class="bg-gray-50 rounded-xl p-6 border border-gray-100">
                <h3 class="font-bold text-granite mb-4 flex items-center gap-2 text-lg !mt-0">
                   <svg class="w-5 h-5 text-sage" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M5 13l4 4L19 7"></path></svg>
                   Smart Features
                </h3>
                <ul class="space-y-3 text-sm text-gray-600 !pl-0 !my-0 list-none">
                  <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                    <span class="w-1.5 h-1.5 rounded-full bg-sage mt-2 flex-shrink-0"></span>
                    <span><strong>Autocomplete suggestions</strong> appear as you type</span>
                  </li>
                  <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                    <span class="w-1.5 h-1.5 rounded-full bg-sage mt-2 flex-shrink-0"></span>
                    <span><strong>Keyboard navigation</strong> with arrow keys (↑↓)</span>
                  </li>
                  <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                    <span class="w-1.5 h-1.5 rounded-full bg-sage mt-2 flex-shrink-0"></span>
                    <span><strong>Confidence indicators</strong> show accuracy</span>
                  </li>
                </ul>
             </div>
             <div class="bg-gray-50 rounded-xl p-6 border border-gray-100">
                <h3 class="font-bold text-granite mb-4 flex items-center gap-2 text-lg !mt-0">
                   <svg class="w-5 h-5 text-sage" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M13 16h-1v-4h-1m1-4h.01M21 12a9 9 0 11-18 0 9 9 0 0118 0z"></path></svg>
                   Helpful Tools
                </h3>
                 <ul class="space-y-3 text-sm text-gray-600 !pl-0 !my-0 list-none">
                  <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                    <span class="w-1.5 h-1.5 rounded-full bg-sage mt-2 flex-shrink-0"></span>
                    <span><strong>Copy button</strong> saves conversions</span>
                  </li>
                  <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                    <span class="w-1.5 h-1.5 rounded-full bg-sage mt-2 flex-shrink-0"></span>
                    <span><strong>Full reference table</strong> at the bottom</span>
                  </li>
                  <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                    <span class="w-1.5 h-1.5 rounded-full bg-sage mt-2 flex-shrink-0"></span>
                    <span><strong>Gym/Outdoor adjustment</strong> built-in</span>
                  </li>
                </ul>
             </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <AffiliateBlock
          title="Breaking through V4-V5? Train finger strength"
          subtitle="Most climbers plateau at V4 because of finger strength, not technique. Hangboards and grip trainers build the strength grades V5+ demand. 15 minutes, 3× per week."
          products={[
            AFFILIATE_PRODUCTS.find(p => p.id === 'power-guidance-hangboard'),
            AFFILIATE_PRODUCTS.find(p => p.id === 'fitbeast-grip-kit'),
          ].filter(Boolean)}
          count={2}
        />

        <!-- Visual Grade Comparison Chart -->
        <div class="bg-white rounded-2xl shadow-xl border border-gray-100 p-8 md:p-10 mb-20 overflow-hidden">
          <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-granite mb-8 text-center flex items-center justify-center gap-3">
            <span class="w-10 h-10 bg-sage/10 rounded-full flex items-center justify-center text-sage">
               <svg class="w-6 h-6" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
              <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M9 19v-6a2 2 0 00-2-2H5a2 2 0 00-2 2v6a2 2 0 002 2h2a2 2 0 002-2zm0 0V9a2 2 0 012-2h2a2 2 0 012 2v10m-6 0a2 2 0 002 2h2a2 2 0 002-2m0 0V5a2 2 0 012-2h2a2 2 0 012 2v14a2 2 0 01-2 2h-2a2 2 0 01-2-2z" />
            </svg>
            </span>
            <span>Quick Grade Comparison</span>
          </h2>
          <div class="overflow-x-auto">
            <table class="w-full text-left border-collapse">
              <thead>
                <tr class="border-b-2 border-gray-100">
                  <th class="px-6 py-4 text-xs font-bold text-gray-500 uppercase tracking-wider">Level</th>
                  <th class="px-6 py-4 text-xs font-bold text-gray-500 uppercase tracking-wider">V-Scale</th>
                  <th class="px-6 py-4 text-xs font-bold text-gray-500 uppercase tracking-wider">Fontainebleau</th>
                  <th class="px-6 py-4 text-xs font-bold text-gray-500 uppercase tracking-wider">UK Tech</th>
                  <th class="px-6 py-4 text-xs font-bold text-gray-500 uppercase tracking-wider">% of Climbers</th>
                </tr>
              </thead>
              <tbody class="divide-y divide-gray-100">
                <tr class="hover:bg-gray-50/50 transition-colors">
                  <td class="px-6 py-5"><span class="inline-block px-3 py-1 bg-blue-100 text-blue-700 rounded-full text-xs font-bold uppercase tracking-wide">Beginner</span></td>
                  <td class="px-6 py-5 font-bold text-gray-900">VB - V3</td>
                  <td class="px-6 py-5 text-gray-600">3 - 5+</td>
                  <td class="px-6 py-5 text-gray-600">4a - 5b</td>
                  <td class="px-6 py-5 text-gray-500 font-medium">~60%</td>
                </tr>
                <tr class="hover:bg-gray-50/50 transition-colors">
                  <td class="px-6 py-5"><span class="inline-block px-3 py-1 bg-purple-100 text-purple-700 rounded-full text-xs font-bold uppercase tracking-wide">Intermediate</span></td>
                  <td class="px-6 py-5 font-bold text-gray-900">V4 - V6</td>
                  <td class="px-6 py-5 text-gray-600">6A - 6C+</td>
                  <td class="px-6 py-5 text-gray-600">5c - 6b</td>
                  <td class="px-6 py-5 text-gray-500 font-medium">~30%</td>
                </tr>
                <tr class="hover:bg-gray-50/50 transition-colors">
                  <td class="px-6 py-5"><span class="inline-block px-3 py-1 bg-orange-100 text-orange-700 rounded-full text-xs font-bold uppercase tracking-wide">Advanced</span></td>
                  <td class="px-6 py-5 font-bold text-gray-900">V7 - V10</td>
                  <td class="px-6 py-5 text-gray-600">7A - 7C+</td>
                  <td class="px-6 py-5 text-gray-600">6c - 7b</td>
                  <td class="px-6 py-5 text-gray-500 font-medium">~8%</td>
                </tr>
                <tr class="hover:bg-gray-50/50 transition-colors">
                  <td class="px-6 py-5"><span class="inline-block px-3 py-1 bg-red-100 text-red-700 rounded-full text-xs font-bold uppercase tracking-wide">Elite</span></td>
                  <td class="px-6 py-5 font-bold text-gray-900">V11+</td>
                  <td class="px-6 py-5 text-gray-600">8A+</td>
                  <td class="px-6 py-5 text-gray-600">7b+</td>
                  <td class="px-6 py-5 text-gray-500 font-medium">~2%</td>
                </tr>
              </tbody>
            </table>
          </div>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400 mt-6 text-center uppercase tracking-wider font-medium">
            Click any grade in the search bar above to see exact conversions
          </p>
        </div>

        <!-- Understanding Bouldering Grade Systems -->
        <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-granite mb-8 mt-20 flex items-center gap-4">
          <span class="w-12 h-12 bg-sage/10 rounded-xl flex items-center justify-center text-sage flex-shrink-0">
             <svg class="w-6 h-6" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
            <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M12 6.253v13m0-13C10.832 5.477 9.246 5 7.5 5S4.168 5.477 3 6.253v13C4.168 18.477 5.754 18 7.5 18s3.332.477 4.5 1.253m0-13C13.168 5.477 14.754 5 16.5 5c1.747 0 3.332.477 4.5 1.253v13C19.832 18.477 18.247 18 16.5 18c-1.746 0-3.332.477-4.5 1.253" />
          </svg>
          </span>
          <span>Understanding Bouldering Grade Systems</span>
        </h2>
        <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-10">
          Bouldering uses three primary grading systems worldwide, each with its own history and regional preferences. Understanding these systems helps you climb confidently anywhere in the world.
        </p>

        <!-- V-Scale -->
        <div class="mb-10">
           <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-granite mb-4">V-Scale (Hueco Scale)</h3>
           <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
             The V-Scale is the dominant system in the United States and increasingly worldwide. Created by John "Verm" Sherman at Hueco Tanks, Texas in the late 1990s, it provides a simple numerical progression: <strong>VB (beginner) → V0 → V1 → V2...</strong> up to <strong>V17</strong> (currently the world's hardest established grade).
           </p>
           <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
             The system is open-ended, meaning new grades (V18, V19, etc.) can be added as climbing difficulty progresses. Unlike sport climbing's YDS system, the V-Scale doesn't use letter modifiers - just clean numbers. However, you'll occasionally see "V0-" or "V0+" to indicate problems on the border between grades.
           </p>
           <div class="bg-gray-50 p-6 rounded-xl border border-gray-100">
             <p class="font-bold text-granite mb-3 text-sm uppercase tracking-wide">V-Scale Grade Ranges:</p>
             <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-600 text-sm !pl-0 !my-0 list-none">
               <li><strong class="text-gray-900">VB-V3:</strong> Beginner (60% of gym climbers)</li>
               <li><strong class="text-gray-900">V4-V6:</strong> Intermediate (30% of gym climbers)</li>
               <li><strong class="text-gray-900">V7-V10:</strong> Advanced (8% of gym climbers)</li>
               <li><strong class="text-gray-900">V11+:</strong> Elite (2% of gym climbers, professional level)</li>
             </ul>
           </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Fontainebleau -->
        <div class="mb-10">
           <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-granite mb-4">Fontainebleau System (Font Grades)</h3>
           <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
             The Fontainebleau system originated at the famous bouldering area near Paris, France. It uses a combination of numbers (1-9) and letters (a, b, c) with optional plus signs: <strong>3 → 4 → 5 → 5+ → 6A → 6A+ → 6B...</strong> up to <strong>9A</strong>.
           </p>
           <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
             Font grades are the standard in Europe and are increasingly used worldwide alongside the V-Scale. Many climbers find Font grades more granular at mid-levels (the V-Scale groups 6A, 6A+, and 6B into just V3 and V4). The system also has a separate technical grade component (lowercase letters: 4a, 5a, 6a) which describes the technical difficulty, though this is less commonly used in modern bouldering.
           </p>
           <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
             <strong>Key difference:</strong> Font grades make finer distinctions at intermediate levels. Where the V-Scale might jump from V5 to V6, Font breaks this into 6B → 6B+ → 6C, giving climbers more specific feedback on progression.
           </p>
        </div>

        <!-- UK Tech Grades -->
        <div class="mb-16">
           <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-granite mb-4">UK Technical Grades</h3>
           <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
             The UK uses a unique technical grading system that focuses on the hardest individual move or sequence: <strong>4a → 4b → 4c → 5a → 5b...</strong> up to <strong>7b-7c</strong> for the hardest boulder problems. This system is similar to French sport climbing grades but typically runs about two letter grades harder (UK 6a ≈ French sport 6c).
           </p>
           <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
             UK Tech grades emphasize the <em>technical crux</em> - the single hardest move - rather than overall difficulty. This makes them particularly useful for describing powerful, crunchy problems with one desperate move versus sustained endurance problems. However, UK Tech grades are rarely used outside the UK, and many modern UK climbers also use V-Scale or Font grades.
           </p>
           <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
             <strong>Conversion note:</strong> UK Tech grades don't extend as high as V-Scale or Font. Elite problems (V14+) typically aren't given UK Tech grades because the system wasn't designed for that level of difficulty.
           </p>
        </div>

        <!-- Why Grades Are Confusing -->
        <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-granite mb-8 mt-20 flex items-center gap-4">
           <span class="w-12 h-12 bg-orange-100 rounded-xl flex items-center justify-center text-orange-500 flex-shrink-0">
              <svg class="w-6 h-6" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
            <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M8.228 9c.549-1.165 2.03-2 3.772-2 2.21 0 4 1.343 4 3 0 1.4-1.278 2.575-3.006 2.907-.542.104-.994.54-.994 1.093m0 3h.01M21 12a9 9 0 11-18 0 9 9 0 0118 0z" />
          </svg>
           </span>
          <span>Why Are Bouldering Grades Confusing?</span>
        </h2>
        
        <div class="bg-orange-50 border border-orange-200 p-8 rounded-xl mb-10">
          <p class="text-orange-900 font-medium leading-relaxed !my-0">
            If you've ever wondered why the V4 at your gym feels easier than outdoor V4, or why different gyms grade problems differently, you're experiencing one of climbing's most frustrating realities: <strong>grades are subjective and inconsistent</strong>.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-x-12 gap-y-8">
           <div>
              <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-granite mb-3">1. Three Different Systems</h3>
              <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed text-sm">
                Unlike many sports with a single universal standard, bouldering has three competing systems (V-Scale, Font, UK Tech), each popular in different regions. Converting between them introduces uncertainty because they don't map perfectly 1:1.
              </p>
           </div>
           <div>
              <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-granite mb-3">2. Subjectivity in Setting</h3>
              <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed text-sm">
                Every route setter has their own interpretation of what "V5" means. Factors like hold style, wall angle, movement style, and setter experience all influence grades. What one gym calls V4 might be V3 or V5 at another gym.
              </p>
           </div>
           <div>
              <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-granite mb-3">3. Personal Strengths</h3>
              <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed text-sm">
                Your body type, height, flexibility, and training history dramatically affect how hard grades feel <em>to you</em>. A 6'2" climber might find a reachy V5 easy, while a shorter climber might excel at technical compression problems.
              </p>
           </div>
           <div>
              <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-granite mb-3">4. Grade Inflation</h3>
              <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed text-sm">
                As climbing equipment, training methods, and community standards evolve, grades shift. A problem graded V8 in 1995 might be considered V6 today because climbers are stronger and more technically proficient.
              </p>
           </div>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-sage/5 border border-sage/20 p-6 rounded-xl mt-10 mb-16 flex items-start gap-4">
          <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-sage mt-1 flex-shrink-0" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M13 16h-1v-4h-1m1-4h.01M21 12a9 9 0 11-18 0 9 9 0 0118 0z"></path></svg>
          <div>
            <p class="font-bold text-granite mb-1 text-sm uppercase tracking-wide">The Bottom Line</p>
            <p class="text-gray-600 text-sm">
              Use grades as a <strong>general guideline</strong>, not an absolute measure. Focus on your own progression, enjoy the climbing, and don't stress too much about whether something "should" feel like a V5 or V6. The journey matters more than the number.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

